			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Fumbling keys and sorry at melee<a name="52811"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 04 11:53 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Two mappable keys are going to make your life a MILLION times easier.  &quot;Cycle Nearest NPC&quot; and &quot;Toggle Last Two Targets&quot;.  Both can be mapped to any key you like.  Go to your options window, the Keyboard Tab, and choose Target from the drop-down list.
<br />

<br />
Where you map these keys depends on how you play now.  I twist using my left hand on the number row of the keyboard for the hotkeys, and navigate with my right hand on my arrow keys.  For me, I mapped &quot;Cycle Nearest NPC&quot; to Caps Lock, and &quot;Toggle Last Targets&quot; to &quot;Q&quot;.  (Some left-twisters will also use &quot;~&quot; for toggle.
<br />

<br />
Cycle Nearest NPC:
<br />

<br />
This key works like &quot;F8&quot; or &quot;Target Nearest NPC&quot;, but it cycles through all the targets you can see in front of you from closest to furthest.  The great thing about this key, is that you can cycle through multiple targets whether they are piled on top of each other, whether there are other players in your way, or whether you are having video lag due to spell particles etc. (you can turn that stuff down or off to help a bunch, btw).  Simply cycle through them, mezzing each on in turn.  (The one that is half dead is the one your group is killing atm, hehe... skip that one).
<br />

<br />
Once you are down to two adds, you can &quot;Toggle&quot; between then with the toggle targets key.  Mez, Toggle, Mez, Toggle etc.  Once you are confident in this, you can start throwing a third song in, Heal, Haste, whatever you think most important.  Mez, Toggle, Mez, Toggle, Buffsong, Mez...
<br />

<br />
Once down to a single add, you can toggle between your mezzed add, and the mob your group is killing.  This enables you to twist two other songs and /assist the main tank while keeping the add mezzed.
<br />

<br />
Mez add, toggle to MT target, /attack, buff1, buff2, Toggle-START MEZ-Toggle, wait for mez to land, buff1, buff2...
<br />

<br />
You only need to target your add when you START the song.  If you do not get interrupted, and let the song land, it will land on the mob you had targetted when you STARTED the song (the add).  You can be smacking your main target the entire time, except for the second it takes to &quot;toggle-start mez-toggle&quot;.  If you are not facing the add, you don't even have to stop attacking (to keep from waking your own mez).  If you mez is resisted though, be ready to toggle back and mez again.
<br />

<br />
Macros to announce Mezzes and stuff are handy.  You can put it on your mez song macro, or have it separate.  That way, it doesn't spam as much, if you simply say &quot;/g %t mezzed&quot; when it is locked down the first time, rather than spamming it every time you refresh it.
<br />

<br />
Your weapons appear to be fine, imo.  For skillups, you want low delay, period.  &quot;Better weapons&quot; usually means a better ratio.  Of course, you will do more melee damage with better ratio weapons, and later on, weapons with nicer proc effects.  But if your melee skills are low, shop for low delay.  Also, bear in mind that once you ding 26 and get your Fear song, you can Snare / Fear solo and bring those skills back up to snuff if they are lagging.  Once they are maxed for your level, just making sure you use all three weapon types while grouped should keep them up nicely, unless you solo kite a bunch of levels and get behind again.
<br />

<br />
Overall though, you should pretty much resign yourself to having pretty sucky melee damage output.  Bards have the worst of all the melee classes.  You make the rest of your group melee better.
<br />

<br />
Hang in there for the solo thing.  Read the guides on solo techniques.  Starting with lvl 26, your solo career will take off.  Keep in mind, that all of our methods are based on the DGH principle:  Don't Get Hit!  So, if you were thinking that you would be able to stand toe-to-toe with mobs and fight them solo, it won't happen.  Honestly, that ability to stand and solo kill mobs goes away for pretty much everyone as you level up, even Pallies who self-heal etc.  There comes a point in the game when the mobs just hit too damned hard.  That point just comes earlier for Bards.
<br />

<br />
But fear not!  Bard are arguably the best solo killing machines in the game.  We simply use our speed and our wits rather than our brawn to do it!</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
