				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Fumbling keys and sorry at melee<a name="52850"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 04 2:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You didn't say what function you or the other bard performed in the group.  It's a good idea to sort that out before starting the adventure.
<br />

<br />
When I do LDoN dungeons, I am normally the puller.  You should ask to be the puller (it's a blast) and ask the MT to tag off your assist.  Use lvl 8 song to lull the mobs in a crowded room.  Most of the time, you will be pulling singles.  If you get more than one, you are normally in a position to mezz them before you get to the group.  I like to keep my groups back from my pulling area to give me some room to mezz.  It's much easier to mezz without 5 other players moving around and blocking your view.  
<br />

<br />
If I was in a group with another bard and I was on CC, I'd go with him/her on the pull and assist with mezzing before they got to the group.
<br />

<br />
Lastly, if the mobs arrive together at your group site, try not to panic.  Everyone has hit points and can take hits.  Focus on one mob and mezz.  Once you have one mezzed, tell the MT to backup (use hotkey).  This will put some separation between your mezzed mob and the others.  Mezz the next mob and tell the MT to backup again.  Once you train the group on what you are doing, they will do it as you tell them a mob is mezzed.  The objective is to put some space between each of the mobs so you can easily target them again for remezzes.
<br />

<br />
I hope I was able to help you a little bit with playing a bard in a dungeon.  This is my method of playing in dungeon groups and I get compliments on my play.</span></td>
